I abdomen","Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Percutaneous drainage","Albendazole"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral discrete lesions are visible in segments V and VI of the liver. There are of low density and fill during the arterial phase of the scan sequence. The filling is not heterogenous and one of the lesions shows a clear peripheral rim of enhancement. The contrast is washed out during the portal phase. This appearance and pattern is characteristic of haemangiomas. Liver haemangiomas are common incidental findings and are found in perhaps 10% of the population. They are usually solitary lesions and found be found in any age group. Small haemangiomas, such as seen in this patient, do not usually cause any symptoms. Larger lesions (\u0026gt;4 cm diameter) may cause symptoms such as right upper quadrant pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo action needs to be taken and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E approach is all that is needed. If there was any diagnostic doubt, an MRI scan could be considered. A fine needle aspiration biopsy would only be done if it was thought that the lesion might be malignant. Percutaneous drainage is reserved for potentially infective lesions. Albendazole is reserved for the treatment of hydatid disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatic haemangiomas are common incidental findings."],"references":["Leon M. Chavez L, Surani S. Hepatic hemangioma: What internists need to know. World J Gastroenterol. 2020; 26: 11\u201320."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20264"},{"type":"media","id":"20265"},{"type":"media","id":"20266"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20264"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.eme